193	65	12	\N	Yes, diabetes can develop rapidly, often within weeks to months after the onset of symptoms. This is often referred to as "new-onset diabetes." The exact cause of new-onset diabetes is often unknown, but it can be triggered by a variety of factors, including: * Hormonal changes, such as those that occur during pregnancy or menopause * Stress and physical inactivity * Certain medications, such as steroids and certain antibiotics * Autoimmune disorders, such as type 1 diabetes * Genetics New-onset diabetes can be divided into two categories: * Type 1 diabetes: an autoimmune condition that is characterized by the destruction of insulin-producing beta cells in the pancreas. * Type 2 diabetes: a metabolic disorder characterized by insulin resistance and impaired insulin secretion, often associated with obesity, physical inactivity, and family history. In some cases, new-onset diabetes can be triggered by a single event, such as a viral infection or a severe illness. In these cases, the body's immune system may react to the infection as a foreign invader, leading to the development of insulin resistance and eventually, diabetes.
