212	80	6	\N	No—after just one day, your blood pressure (BP) is unlikely to be at goal yet, though you may see some reduction.\n\n**What to expect:**\n- **Onset:** Lisinopril starts lowering BP within a few hours of the first dose.\n- **Full effect:** It typically takes **2–4 weeks** (and sometimes several dose adjustments) to reach your target BP. Steady state is usually achieved in about a week.\n- **First-dose caution:** Some people experience a larger drop with the very first dose (dizziness or lightheadedness), especially if you’re also on a diuretic or dehydrated. If you feel faint, sit or lie down and contact your clinician.\n\n**Next steps:**\n- Check your BP at the same time daily (e.g., morning and evening) and keep a log.\n- Don’t panic if numbers aren’t perfect yet; give it time.\n- Contact your prescriber if your BP is extremely high (e.g., ≥180/120) or if you have symptoms like severe headache, chest pain, or neurological changes.\n- Attend your follow-up appointment (usually in 2–4 weeks) to assess if the dose needs adjustment.\n\n**Helpful tip:** Limit salt, avoid NSAIDs like ibuprofen (which can raise BP and stress kidneys with ACE inhibitors), and rise slowly from sitting/lying positions to prevent dizziness.\n\nIf you’re feeling well, continue the medication as prescribed—consistency is key.
