214	82	6	\N	The best time to take trazodone is **usually at bedtime**, especially if you're taking it for insomnia or if your doctor prescribed it to help with sleep.\n\n**Key timing tips:**\n- **Bedtime**: Trazodone causes significant drowsiness/sedation, so taking it 30–60 minutes before sleep helps you fall asleep and reduces fall risk.\n- **With food**: Take it with a light snack or meal to decrease dizziness or lightheadedness when standing up.\n- **Be consistent**: Take it at the same time every night.\n\n**Important cautions:**\n- **Morning grogginess**: You may feel drowsy the next morning, particularly at higher doses or if you take it too late at night.\n- **Avoid alcohol**: Do not combine with alcohol or other sedatives.\n- **Driving/operating machinery**: Don't drive until you know how it affects you the next day.\n\n*Exception*: If you're taking trazodone specifically for depression (rather than insomnia) and your doctor prescribed divided daily doses, follow their specific instructions—though one nightly dose is still common to minimize daytime sleepiness.\n\nAlways follow your prescriber's specific instructions, as timing can vary based on your dose and condition.
215	83	6	\N	Not necessarily—Metrogel (metronidazole vaginal gel) doesn't work for everyone, even when the diagnosis is correct.\n\n**Why it might fail despite being BV:**\n- **Biofilms:** The bacteria causing BV (mainly *Gardnerella*) can form protective biofilms on the vaginal wall, shielding them from antibiotics. This is a common cause of recurrent or persistent BV.\n- **Resistance:** While less common with metronidazole than other antibiotics, resistant strains do occur.\n- **Incomplete treatment:** Missing doses, stopping early, or having menstrual bleeding wash out the gel can reduce efficacy.\n- **Reinfection:** New or untreated sexual partners can reintroduce bacteria (though BV isn't strictly an STI, semen and new partners can disrupt vaginal pH).\n- **Co-infections:** BV often coexists with other infections (like trichomoniasis or yeast) that metronidazole doesn't treat.\n\n**Also consider:**\nIf Metrogel didn't help, the diagnosis could be wrong. Symptoms similar to BV can be caused by:\n- Trichomoniasis (requires different medication)\n- Yeast infection\n- Cytolytic vaginosis\n- Atrophic vaginitis (if menopausal)\n- Desquamative inflammatory vaginitis\n\n**Next steps:**\n- Return for a repeat wet mount/NAAT testing to confirm the diagnosis\n- If confirmed BV: Consider oral metronidazole, tinidazole, or clindamycin (oral or vaginal)\n- For recurrent cases: Extended pulse-dose therapy or boric acid protocols may be needed\n- Consider treating male partners in recurrent cases (evidence is mixed, but sometimes helpful)\n\n**Bottom line:** Treatment failure happens in roughly 15–30% of BV cases initially, so not responding to Metrogel doesn't rule out BV—but it does warrant follow-up testing to confirm what you're actually treating.\n\n*This is general information; please consult your healthcare provider for personalized evaluation.*
