219	70	2	\N	Right lower abdominal pain in a 33-year-old female can have several possible causes, including:\n\n### **Common Causes:**\n1. **Appendicitis**  \n   - Sudden, severe pain starting near the navel and moving to the lower right side.  \n   - Nausea, vomiting, fever, and loss of appetite may occur.  \n   - Requires urgent medical attention (risk of rupture).  \n\n2. **Ovarian Cysts or Torsion**  \n   - Dull or sharp pain, especially if a cyst ruptures or the ovary (torsion).  \n   - May be associated with menstrual cycle changes.  \n\n3. **Ectopic Pregnancy**  \n   - If sexually active, this is a medical emergency (especially with missed periods or vaginal bleeding).  \n\n4. **Pelvic Inflammatory Disease (PID)**  \n   - Infection of reproductive organs, often with fever, discharge, or pain during sex.  \n\n5. **Kidney Stones or UTI**  \n   - Flank pain radiating to the groin, painful urination, or blood in urine.  \n\n6. **Irritable Bowel Syndrome (IBS) or Constipation**  \n   - Cramping, bloating, and changes in bowel habits.  \n\n7. **Diverticulitis**  \n   - More common in older adults but possible; fever and constipation may occur.  \n\n### **When to Seek Immediate Care:**  \n- Severe/worsening pain  \n- Fever, vomiting, or dizziness  \n- Signs of shock (pale skin, rapid heartbeat)  \n- Possible pregnancy  \n\nIf pain is mild but persistent, see a doctor for evaluation (ultrasound, blood tests, or CT may be needed). Avoid self-diagnosis—some conditions require urgent treatment.  \n\nWould you like help identifying any other symptoms?
