233	67	11	\N	The usual Saxenda (liraglutide for weight management) titration is to stay on each dose for 1 week before increasing. A common schedule is:\n\n- Week 1: 0.6 mg daily  \n- Week 2: 1.2 mg daily  \n- Week 3: 1.8 mg daily  \n- Week 4: 2.4 mg daily  \n- Week 5 and after: 3.0 mg daily (maintenance)\n\nSo you wait at least 7 days at a dose before moving to the next. If you have significant nausea, vomiting, or other intolerable side effects, your prescriber may advise staying longer at a lower dose or slowing the up‑titration. Don’t exceed 3.0 mg/day and follow your clinician’s instructions. Contact your prescriber right away for severe abdominal pain, persistent vomiting, signs of pancreatitis, or other serious symptoms.
234	68	11	\N	Short answer depends on the pill strength and your situation. Most OTC ibuprofen tablets are 200 mg; common safe dosing for adults is:\n\n- Take 1–2 tablets (200–400 mg) every 4–6 hours as needed.\n- Do not exceed 6 tablets (1200 mg) in 24 hours unless your doctor tells you otherwise.\n\nIf a doctor is supervising, higher daily amounts (often up to 2,400 mg/day, and in some settings up to 3,200 mg/day) may be used for short periods — but that increases risk of side effects.\n\nFor children use weight-based dosing (not adult pills): 5–10 mg/kg every 6–8 hours, maximum about 40 mg/kg/day.\n\nImportant cautions\n- Don’t take ibuprofen if you have an allergy to NSAIDs, active stomach/intestinal bleeding or ulcers, severe kidney disease, or in late pregnancy unless directed by a clinician.\n- Use caution (and check with your prescriber) if you take blood thinners (warfarin), aspirin, certain blood pressure medicines (ACE inhibitors, ARBs, diuretics), or have heart disease.\n- Stop and seek medical care if you get severe stomach pain, black/tarry stools, vomiting blood, new shortness of breath, swelling, rash, or ringing in the ears.\n\nIf you tell me your age, weight (for a child), what strength pill you have, and any medical conditions or other medicines you take, I can give a more specific recommendation.
235	69	11	\N	Short answer: start low and use the smallest dose that helps. For most adults that’s 0.5–3 mg taken about 30–60 minutes before bedtime. If that helps, stay at the lowest effective dose. If not effective after a week you can increase gradually (commonly up to 3–5 mg). Talk to your clinician before using higher doses.\n\nKey points to consider\n- Start low: 0.5–1 mg is a reasonable first dose for sleep onset. Many people do well with 0.3–1 mg.  \n- Typical effective range: 0.5–3 mg for most adults.  \n- Upper limits: 3–5 mg is commonly used; some people take up to 10 mg but higher doses increase risk of next‑day grogginess and side effects. Ask a clinician before exceeding 5–10 mg.  \n- Older adults: often need lower doses (for example 0.3–0.5 mg) because they can be more sensitive and are at higher risk of morning drowsiness.  \n- Timing: take immediate‑release melatonin about 30–60 minutes before bedtime. For circadian phase shifts (e.g., jet lag, delayed sleep phase) timing can be different — discuss with a clinician for a tailored schedule.  \n- Formulation: immediate release helps with falling asleep; extended release may help if you wake in the middle of the night.\n\nSafety and cautions\n- Common side effects: daytime sleepiness, dizziness, headache, vivid dreams, nausea.  \n- Don’t mix with alcohol or combine with other sedatives (benzodiazepines, opioids, strong antihistamines) without medical advice.  \n- Melatonin can interact with some medications (anticoagulants, diabetes meds, immunosuppressants, contraceptives, etc.). Check with your provider or pharmacist if you take regular prescription drugs.  \n- Pregnancy, breastfeeding, young children, serious medical conditions: consult a clinician before use. For children, use only under pediatric guidance.  \n- If insomnia is chronic (weeks–months), worsening, or affecting daily life, see a healthcare professional to look for underlying causes and discuss safer long‑term treatments.\n\nIf you want,