236	70	11	\N	Right lower abdominal pain in a 33-year‑old woman can come from many causes. I can’t diagnose over text, but here are the common possibilities, how to tell them apart, what to do now, and when to seek urgent care.\n\nCommon causes\n- Appendicitis — often starts as dull periumbilical pain that moves to the right lower quadrant, with nausea, fever, loss of appetite, and localized tenderness (rebound/guarding).\n- Ovarian torsion — sudden, severe unilateral pelvic pain with nausea/vomiting; ovary may be enlarged on ultrasound. Surgical emergency.\n- Ruptured ovarian cyst — sudden sharp pain, sometimes light vaginal bleeding; can cause internal bleeding.\n- Ectopic pregnancy — consider in any woman of childbearing potential with abdominal pain and/or vaginal bleeding; may have shoulder pain, dizziness if bleeding.\n- Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) / tubo‑ovarian abscess — usually bilateral pelvic pain, fever, abnormal discharge, recent STI risk.\n- Urinary causes — UTI or ureteral (kidney) stone: dysuria, frequency, or colicky flank-to‑groin pain and hematuria.\n- Gastrointestinal — gastroenteritis, constipation, inflammatory bowel disease, or (less commonly at this age) cecal diverticulitis or mesenteric adenitis.\n- Gynecologic cyclic pain — mittelschmerz (ovulation pain) or endometriosis (chronic cyclical pain).\n\nKey clues from history/exam that help\n- Pregnancy test positive → prioritize ectopic pregnancy and obstetric/gynecologic causes.\n- Sudden severe onset with vomiting → think torsion or rupture or renal colic.\n- Fever and foul discharge → consider PID or abscess.\n- Pain migration from umbilicus to RLQ, tenderness at McBurney point, rebound → appendicitis.\n- Blood in urine → stone or UTI.\n- Recent intercourse or STI risk → PID or ectopic.\n\nWhat to do now\n- If you could be pregnant, do a pregnancy test immediately.\n- Seek urgent evaluation (emergency department or same‑day clinic) if you have any of: severe or worsening pain, fever, fainting/dizziness, fainting, heavy vaginal bleeding, progressive vomiting, inability to pass stool/gas, or signs of peritonitis (rigid abdomen).\n- If pain is mild and stable, make a prompt appointment with your primary care or gynecology clinic. Typical initial tests include: urine pregnancy test, urine dip/culture, CBC, CRP, pelvic exam, STI testing, and imaging (pelvic/transvaginal ultrasound is first-line for gynecologic causes; CT abdomen/pelvis often used for suspected appendicitis/other abdominal causes if not pregnant).\n\nIf you’d like, tell me:\n- Exact location, how it started and how severe it is,\n- Associated symptoms (fever, nausea, vomiting, vaginal bleeding/discharge, urinary symptoms, bowel changes),\n- Last menstrual period and contraceptive/sexual history,\n- Any previous similar episodes or abdominal surgery.\nWith that I can help prioritize next steps.
237	71	11	\N	Short answer: No — an isolated rise in ALT itself does not cause diarrhea. ALT is a blood marker that signals liver cell injury; it’s a lab finding, not a symptom-causing toxin.\n\nWhy you might see both elevated ALT and diarrhea\n- They can occur together if the same underlying condition causes both. Examples:\n  - Viral hepatitis or some systemic infections can cause GI symptoms (nausea, abdominal pain, sometimes diarrhea).\n  - Some medications or antibiotics can raise ALT and also cause diarrhea as a side effect.\n  - Advanced or cholestatic liver disease can cause fat malabsorption or pale/greasy stools (steatorrhea), which may be perceived as diarrhea.\n  - Metabolic, autoimmune, or infiltrative diseases can involve the liver and gut in different ways.\n- They can also be unrelated problems that happen at the same time.\n\nWhat to do next\n- If you feel otherwise well and the ALT is only mildly elevated, common steps include repeating the test in 6–12 weeks and reviewing risk factors (alcohol, medications/supplements, obesity, viral hepatitis exposure).\n- A clinician will usually check a liver panel (AST, ALP, GGT, bilirubin), viral hepatitis serologies, metabolic/iron studies and may order an ultrasound or other tests depending on risk factors and results.\n- For diarrhea, evaluate timing, character (bloody, greasy, watery), duration, fever, recent antibiotics, travel, or foods. Stool studies or further GI workup may be needed if it is severe or persistent.\n\nWhen to seek urgent care\n- Jaundice (yellowing of skin/eyes), very dark urine, pale stools, severe abdominal pain, high fever, heavy bleeding, fainting, or rapid weight loss — these require prompt medical attention.\n\nIf you’d like, tell me your ALT value, how long it’s been elevated, any medications or recent illnesses, and details about the diarrhea (onset, appearance, frequency), and I can give more tailored guidance.
238	72	11	\N	Short answer: get your routine vaccines up to date, plus hepatitis A. Depending on where in Brazil you’ll go and what you’ll do, you may also need or want yellow fever, hepatitis B, typhoid, rabies or malaria prevention. See below — and tell me your exact itinerary and vaccination history and I’ll give a tailored plan.\n\nWhat most healthy adult travelers should do\n- Routine vaccines: confirm you are up to date on MMR (measles-mumps-rubella), Tdap (tetanus-diphtheria-pertussis; booster every 10 years), varicella if no history, and annual influenza. Measles outbreaks occur occasionally — two MMR doses if not already immune.\n- COVID-19: be up to date with recommended COVID-19 vaccine doses/boosters.\n- Hepatitis A: recommended for all travelers to Brazil (single dose pre-travel gives good short‑term protection; complete the series afterward).\n- Hepatitis B: recommended for unvaccinated travelers who may have sex with new partners, need medical care, get tattoos/piercings, or have prolonged stays — consider the vaccine series.\n\nLocation- and activity-dependent vaccines / prevention\n- Yellow fever vaccine: recommended if you will visit Amazon and many interior/rural states (eg, Amazonas, Pará, Acre, Rondônia, Roraima, Amapá, parts of Mato Grosso, Tocantins and others). Not usually needed for short stays confined to large cities (Rio, São Paulo) unless you visit endemic areas. If recommended, it must be given at least 10 days before travel. Some entry/exit requirements may change, so check current travel health advice.\n- Typhoid vaccine: consider if you will eat in small towns/rural areas or stay with locals for extended time; not routinely required for short stays in major cities.\n- Rabies pre-exposure vaccination: consider if you’ll be doing outdoor/remote work, extended rural stays, or expect contact with animals. Post-exposure management is simpler after pre-exposure vaccination.\n- Malaria: no vaccine routinely recommended, but malaria occurs in the Amazon region. If you’ll visit that area, you may need antimalarial prophylaxis (choice depends on exact location). Mosquito avoidance is important.\n\nTiming and next steps\n- You said you leave in ~1 month — make an appointment with a travel clinic or your primary care provider as soon as possible. Some vaccines need multiple doses or 10+ days to be effective (yellow fever).\n- If you want, tell me: exact cities/regions to visit, length of stay, planned activities (rural/urban, rainforest, volunteer/medical work, animal contact), pregnancy or immune problems, and which vaccines you’ve already had. I’ll give a personalized list and an action plan.
239	73	11	\N	You’re right to notice that true benign prostatic enlargement (benign prostatic hyperplasia, BPH) is very uncommon at age 22. BPH is primarily a condition of middle‑aged and older men (usually from the 50s onward).\n\nThat said, a prostate that feels enlarged or causes urinary symptoms in a young man can have other causes, including:\n- Prostatitis (acute bacterial or chronic/chronic pelvic pain syndrome) — common in younger men and can make the prostate tender/swollen and cause urinary pain, frequency, urgency, fever.  \n- Urinary tract infection or an STI (which can involve the prostate).  \n- Prostatic cysts or other structural anomalies (rare).  \n- Urethral stricture or bladder problems that make you feel obstructed.  \n- Prostate cancer is very unusual under 40 but not impossible; risk is higher with a strong family history or certain genetic mutations.\n\nWhat a doctor will usually do\n- Ask about symptoms (urinary frequency, urgency, weak stream, pain, fever, blood in urine).  \n- Perform a urine dipstick and urine culture; sometimes STI testing.  \n- A focused prostate exam (DRE) and possibly a pelvic/renal ultrasound or bladder scan (to check residual urine).  \n- PSA blood testing is generally not routinely done in men under 40 unless there is a specific concern (family history, suspicious exam).\n\nWhen to seek urgent care\n- You can’t pass urine (acute retention).  \n- High fever, chills, severe pain (possible acute bacterial prostatitis).  \n- Heavy bleeding in the urine.\n\nIf you’d like, tell me what symptoms you’re having and any family history of prostate cancer and I can help you decide what to mention to your GP or whether you should be seen urgently.
