243	77	11	\N	Short answer: Yes. You can get shingles more than once.\n\nDetails:\n- Shingles (herpes zoster) is a reactivation of the varicella‑zoster virus that stays dormant after chickenpox. Reactivation can recur months or years later.\n- Recurrences are less common than a first episode in healthy people but become more likely with age and with weakened immunity (e.g., cancer, HIV, chemotherapy, long‑term steroids, other immunosuppressive drugs), and possibly after severe stress or other illness.\n- Antiviral treatment (acyclovir, valacyclovir, famciclovir) started early (ideally within 72 hours of the rash) reduces severity and duration; see a clinician promptly if you suspect shingles.\n- Vaccination (recombinant zoster vaccine, Shingrix) substantially lowers the risk of a first episode and of recurrence and is recommended for most adults 50+ and for many people with weakened immunity; it’s recommended even if you’ve already had shingles.\n\nIf you’ve had shingles more than once or have risk factors for recurrence, check with your healthcare provider to evaluate immune status and discuss vaccination and prevention.
244	78	11	\N	Here are the key things to know about taking colchicine for gout. Follow the exact directions your doctor or the prescription label gives — these are general guidelines only.\n\nHow to take colchicine for an acute gout attack\n- Common regimen: 1.2 mg at the first sign of an attack (usually two 0.6 mg tablets), then 0.6 mg one hour later.  \n- Do not exceed 1.8 mg in one hour and do not take more than 2.4 mg in any 24‑hour period.  \n- After the initial dosing some doctors continue 0.6 mg once or twice daily until the attack has clearly settled (often a few days). Follow your doctor’s instructions about how long to continue.\n\nHow to take colchicine to prevent attacks (prophylaxis)\n- Typical dose: 0.6 mg once daily or 0.6 mg twice daily (many people use 0.6 mg once daily).  \n- When starting urate‑lowering therapy (allopurinol, etc.) colchicine prophylaxis is often continued for several months (your doctor will tell you how long).\n\nWhat to watch for and precautions\n- Common side effects: diarrhea, nausea, abdominal pain. If you get severe diarrhea or vomiting stop the drug and call your doctor.  \n- Serious but less common risks: muscle pain or weakness, numbness, tingling, unusual bruising or bleeding, fever or signs of infection — these can indicate toxicity or bone‑marrow suppression; stop the drug and seek medical advice.  \n- Don’t exceed the recommended dose. Colchicine overdose can be life‑threatening.\n\nInteractions and dose adjustments\n- Colchicine interacts with many medicines (notably strong CYP3A4 inhibitors and P‑glycoprotein inhibitors such as clarithromycin, certain azole antifungals, HIV protease inhibitors, cyclosporine, verapamil, diltiazem, and some others). These combinations can cause dangerous colchicine levels.  \n- People with severe kidney or liver disease usually need a reduced dose or should avoid colchicine.  \n- Colchicine can increase the risk of muscle injury when used with statins or fibrates.  \n- Tell your doctor